                     </persName>
                     
                  , his master
            </rs>.</p>
               <p>JOHN HOPKINS. I live in <placeName id="t18310217-156-crimeloc941">Shoreditch</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18310217-156-crimeloc941" type="placeName" value="Shoreditch"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18310217-156-crimeloc941" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18310217-156-off939 t18310217-156-crimeloc941"></join>, and am a <rs id="t18310217-156-viclabel942" type="occupation">linen-draper</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18310217-156-victim1560 t18310217-156-viclabel942"></join>; the prisoner was my <rs id="t18310217-156-deflabel943" type="occupation">porter</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18310217-156-defend1558 t18310217-156-deflabel943"></join> - he slept in the shop with another person. On the night of the 21st of January we found we had been robbed of 16s.; and on the Saturday night following I marked a quantity of money, and left it in the desk - on the Sunday morning I went to the desk, and missed one half-sovereign, two half-crowns, and four shillings in silver; I had marked the silver, but not the half-sovereign - I sent for an officer, and had the two porters examined, up stairs; he found on the prisoner this half-sovereign, and the two marked half-crowns.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18310217-156-person1561">
                  THOMAS 
                  GARTON
               <interp inst="t18310217-156-person1561" type="surname" value="GARTON"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18310217-156-person1561" type="given" value="THOMAS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18310217-156-person1561" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am an officer. I found on the prisoner the half-sovereign and two half-crowns, which the prosecutor spoke to, and 1l. 2s. 6d. besides.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18310217-156-person1562">
                  JAMES 
                  SIMMONDS
               <interp inst="t18310217-156-person1562" type="surname" value="SIMMONDS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18310217-156-person1562" type="given" value="JAMES"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18310217-156-person1562" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I produce these gloves and handkerchief, and the key of the box, which were found in the prisoner's trunks.</p>
               <p>MR. HOPKINS. These gloves and handkerchief were taken from the prisoner's trunk, up stairs, in the dressing-room; the prisoner said they were mine, but I have no mark on them - these half-crowns have my mark on them, and the half-sovereign had a little mark at the end of the A, which I saw - I did not put any mark on it.</p>
               <p>Cross-examined by MR. PHILLIPS. Q. Did not the prisoner say, "This handkerchief is mine?" A. No. he said, "It is yours, Sir;" I had not left any sovereign in the desk - the cashier, generally, takes out all the money at eight o'clock; he did so that night, but I was not there - I put the money into the desk, between eleven and twelve; the prisoner might have access to the desk, but he had no business there - he did not say, in my presence, that he had put a sovereign in, and taken the change out - I had a very good character with him.</p>
               <p>JURY. Q. Was it possible for him to have put a sovereign into the desk? A. I counted all that the desk contained when I marked the money; the sum total was about 2l. 15s., and from that 17s. was abstracted.</p>
               <p>The prisoner received an excellent character.</p>
               <p>GUILTY. Aged 30.</p>
               <p>
